const framing = pick(FRAMINGS);
const hook = pick(HOOKS);

const video_prompt = `
Write a complete spoken math and machine learning narration for a Manim three dimensional visual explainer.

Visual topic:
"${subject}"

Angle:
${angle}

Structure:
${framing}

Opening style:
${hook}

Output only the spoken narration. No markdown, no bullets, no headings, no symbols, no digits.

Every number must be written as spoken words. Every figure, formula reference, and measurement must be written exactly as a human would say it aloud.

==============================
LENGTH
==============================
Write between one thousand one hundred and one thousand three hundred words.
Do not write fewer than one thousand words.
Do not exceed one thousand four hundred words under any circumstances.
This is a hard limit tied to a downstream text-to-speech character cap -- going over will break audio generation.

This is words, not characters.
This is words, not characters.
This is words, not characters.

This is a long-form narration.
Do not write a short summary.
Do not compress the explanation into a few paragraphs.

Write at least eight paragraphs.
Each paragraph must make one clear point with at least three sentences.

==============================
CORE REQUIREMENT
==============================

This script must obviously imply Manim three dimensional visuals.

The narration must not sound like a normal abstract lesson that could be rendered as flat text.

The visual topic is already a moving three dimensional scene. Keep returning to that scene throughout the explanation.

Every major paragraph must include at least one visible spatial object or visible motion when it is accurate:
points,
arrows,
vectors,
axes,
angle arcs,
grids,
planes,
surfaces,
clouds,
clusters,
paths,
rotations,
projections,
connections,
transformations,
or glowing regions in space.

Do not describe ordinary real-world scenes like people walking, classrooms, parks, offices, rooms, faces, or characters.

This is not cinematic storytelling.
This is mathematical geometry made visible.

==============================
HOW TO OPEN
==============================

The opening four sentences must follow this exact pattern.

Sentence one:
State the misconception or weak mental model that makes this concept confusing. State it as a fact, not a question.

Sentence two:
Immediately introduce the visual object from the topic, using three dimensional spatial language.

Sentence three:
Name what the moving objects represent mathematically or mechanically.

Sentence four:
Open a tension loop by describing what changes in the scene when the correct mechanism starts working.

After sentence four, transition into teaching the concept clearly without announcing that you are doing so.

Good opening examples:

"Embeddings feel mysterious because most explanations describe meaning without showing where that meaning lives. Imagine a glowing cloud of points floating in space, where related ideas drift close together and unrelated ideas move apart. Each point is not a definition, it is a position the model can compare. Once the cloud starts forming neighborhoods, meaning stops sounding magical and starts looking like geometry."

"Attention sounds vague when people explain it as focus. A better picture is a field of floating word cards, each sending arrows toward the others and lighting up the paths that matter most. Those arrows represent query and key comparisons, not human attention. When the strongest paths brighten, information starts flowing through the sentence instead of sitting in isolated words."

"PCA feels like deleting information because beginners picture data as a spreadsheet losing columns. The better picture is a three dimensional cloud rotating until one glowing direction catches most of its shape. The method is not throwing space away at random, it is choosing the view where the cloud spreads the most. Once that direction appears, compression starts looking like rotation before reduction."

==============================
HOW TO TEACH
==============================

Teach the concept directly after the opening four sentences.

Use the visual topic as the backbone of the whole narration.

Do not turn the narration into technical scene directions.
Do not say "show this on screen."
Do not say "the animation should."
Do not write Manim code.

Instead, explain the concept in visual language so the renderer can infer the three dimensional scene naturally.

The explanation must do all of the following:

Name the naive mental model.
Show why that mental model fails.
Build the correct spatial model.
Explain what each visible object represents.
Explain the real mathematical or machine learning mechanism.
Use one concrete example if it makes the concept clearer.
Connect the visual motion back to what the model is actually doing.
End with a practical mental model the viewer can keep.

Vary the approach paragraph by paragraph.
Some paragraphs explain.
Some build intuition.
Some correct a mistake.
Some describe the visual transformation.
Some connect the geometry back to the actual mechanism.

==============================
VISUAL DISCIPLINE
==============================

Prefer visual language that creates real Manim objects:

a point cloud rotating in space,
two vectors closing their angle,
a grid stretching under a transformation,
a surface folding or unfolding,
tokens connected by glowing paths,
a plane slicing through a cloud,
a projection dropping points onto a surface,
clusters separating into neighborhoods,
an arrow staying fixed while space bends,
a path moving through latent space,
noise particles becoming structure,
axes rotating toward useful directions.

Do not fake literal three dimensional meaning where it would be inaccurate.

When discussing high-dimensional space, treat the three dimensional scene as an honest visual analogy.
Make clear through phrasing that the visible space is a simplified picture of a deeper geometry.

Avoid flat-script language.
Avoid generic textbook narration.
Avoid long abstract paragraphs with no visible object.
Avoid explaining only definitions.
Avoid explaining only history.
Avoid explaining only applications.

==============================
NUMBER AND FORMULA PACING
==============================

Use spoken figures only when they make a point more concrete.
Most lessons need no more than six figures total.
After any paragraph containing a figure, write at least one paragraph with no figure before the next one.
Never put two figures in the same paragraph.
Never read out raw formula notation. Translate it into plain spoken language.

==============================
HOW TO CLOSE
==============================

The second to last paragraph summarizes the single most important shift in thinking this video creates. No recap of figures. One clear takeaway about geometry, intuition, or mechanism.

The final paragraph must land the visual mechanism from the video. Do not introduce a new topic. Do not point to a next lesson. Do not sound like a course announcement. End with the clearest mental picture the viewer should keep.

==============================
STYLE
==============================

Write the way a sharp person who genuinely understands the topic explains it to someone who almost gets it but keeps missing the picture.

Direct.
Concrete.
Visual.
Precise.
No theatrics.
No filler.
No generic motivational ending.
No textbook voice.
No ordinary cinematic scene.
No characters.
No people.
No fake drama.

The goal is not to cover everything.
The goal is to make the mechanism click so strongly that the viewer can picture the three dimensional scene.
